subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis
. Carapace transversely subovate (
Figs. 3A
, 
4A
, 
5A
); surface covered with short pubescence, never with long setae; regions on dorsal carapace surface almost undiscernible, with only shallow H-shaped gastric grooves barely visible (
Fig. 5A
); front margin wide, bilobed, no lateral lobule present, confluent with supraorbital margin (
Fig. 5A
); anterolateral margin relatively short, entire, with small granules (
Fig. 5A
); posterior margin of epistome almost entire, with median lobe triangular with shallow median cleft, confluent with lateral margins (
Fig. 5B
); third maxilliped with short, subrectangular ischium, merus quadrate, anteroexternal angle rounded, not auriculiform (
Fig. 5D
); ambulatory legs proportionately slender, long, with distinct dactylo-propodal lock (
Figs. 3A–C
, 
4A, B
); female pleonal somite longitudinally narrow, wide, reaching to coxae of last ambulatory legs, somite 1 tapering along lateral margins (
Fig. 5E
); vulvae large, subovate, occupying anterior two-thirds of sternite 6, touching suture with sternite 5 (
Fig. 3D
).
